# Review of `app.js` — Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

The file is small, but it has several gaps typical of a minimal Express setup. Here are concrete improvements, grouped by concern.

## 1. Missing global error handling

Express will crash or leak stack traces without an error middleware.

```js
// Catch-all error handler (must have 4 args)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log server-side only
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});

// 404 handler
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});

// Crash-proof the process
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => console.error('unhandledRejection', reason));
process.on('uncaughtException',  (err)    => console.error('uncaughtException', err));
```

## 2. No input validation

Neither route currently accepts input, but once you add query/body params you should validate strictly. Use a schema library such as `zod` or `joi`, and **never trust `req.query`, `req.params`, or `req.body`**.

```js
const { z } = require('zod');

const UserIdSchema = z.coerce.number().int().positive().max(1e9);

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  const parsed = UserIdSchema.safeParse(req.params.id);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid id' });
  // ... use parsed.data
});
```

Also add `express.json({ limit: '10kb' })` before any body-parsing route to prevent large-payload DoS.

## 3. Security headers & hardening

Add defensive middleware:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const cors = require('cors');

app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(cors({ origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN ?? false })); // explicit allowlist
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

## 4. Sensitive data exposure

`/users` returns email addresses unconditionally. Even in a demo:
- Require authentication (e.g., a JWT/session middleware).
- Return only fields the caller is authorized to see.
- Never log PII or full request bodies.

```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  if (!req.headers.authorization) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  // verify token...
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

## 5. Configuration & startup

- Port is hardcoded. Use `process.env.PORT` with a numeric fallback.
- `app.listen` has no error handler; bind failures are silent.
- `module.exports = app` is good for testing, but don't also call `listen` in the same file — split into `app.js` (exports the app) and `server.js` (calls listen). This prevents tests from starting real sockets.

```js
// server.js
const app = require('./app');
const port = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
const server = app.listen(port, () => console.log(`listening on ${port}`));
server.on('error', (err) => { console.error(err); process.exit(1); });
```

## 6. Async route safety

Once routes become `async`, unhandled rejections bypass Express error handling. Wrap handlers or use `express-async-errors`:

```js
require('express-async-errors'); // top of file
```

## 7. Response consistency

Standardize a response envelope so errors and successes are parseable:

```js
// success
res.json({ data: [...] });
// error
res.status(400).json({ error: { code: 'INVALID_INPUT', message: '...' } });
```

Also set `res.type('application/json')` explicitly if you ever render other content types.

---

### Summary checklist

- [ ] Add error-handling middleware + 404 handler
- [ ] Handle `unhandledRejection` / `uncaughtException`
- [ ] Validate all inputs with a schema library
- [ ] Limit body size (`express.json({ limit: '10kb' })`)
- [ ] Add `helmet`, `cors` allowlist, rate limiting, `disable('x-powered-by')`
- [ ] Require authentication on `/users`; minimize returned fields
- [ ] Move `listen` out of `app.js`; use `process.env.PORT`
- [ ] Use `express-async-errors` or wrap async handlers
- [ ] Standardize response envelope

