# Code Review: `app.js`

Here's an analysis of `app.js` with suggested improvements focused on error handling, input validation, and security best practices.

## Current Issues

### 1. No error handling middleware
Express won't catch async errors or route failures gracefully — a thrown error can crash the process or leak stack traces to clients.

### 2. No security headers
Missing hardening headers (CSP, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.) that `helmet` provides out of the box.

### 3. No rate limiting
`/users` and `/health` are open to abuse/DoS.

### 4. No input validation
Although the current routes don't accept user input, there's no validation middleware in place for when routes are added. `express.json()` isn't even wired up, and body size limits aren't configured.

### 5. Sensitive data exposure
`/users` returns emails unconditionally — no auth, no field filtering. In production this is a PII leak.

### 6. Hardcoded port & no graceful shutdown
Port `3000` is hardcoded; no `SIGTERM`/`SIGINT` handling means in-flight requests get dropped on deploy.

### 7. No logging / request IDs
Errors can't be traced without structured logging.

### 8. CORS not explicitly configured
Defaults can be surprising depending on deployment.

---

## Suggested Rewrite

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const { body, validationResult } = require('express-validator');

const app = express();

// --- Security & parsing middleware ---
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));           // cap body size
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));

// --- Rate limiting ---
app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));

// --- Routes ---
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
});

app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  // Strip sensitive fields by default
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob' },
  ]);
});

// Example: validated input route
app.post(
  '/users',
  body('name').isString().trim().isLength({ min: 1, max: 100 }).escape(),
  body('email').isEmail().normalizeEmail(),
  (req, res, next) => {
    const errors = validationResult(req);
    if (!errors.isEmpty()) {
      return res.status(400).json({ errors: errors.array() });
    }
    // ... handle create
    res.status(201).json({ ok: true });
  }
);

// --- 404 handler ---
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' }));

// --- Centralized error handler ---
// eslint-disable-next-line no-unused-vars
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error({ msg: 'unhandled_error', err: err.message, stack: err.stack });
  const status = err.status || 500;
  // Never leak stack traces in production
  res.status(status).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Internal Server Error' : err.message,
  });
});

// --- Graceful shutdown ---
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const server = app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});

for (const sig of ['SIGINT', 'SIGTERM']) {
  process.on(sig, () => {
    console.log(`${sig} received, shutting down`);
    server.close(() => process.exit(0));
    setTimeout(() => process.exit(1), 10_000).unref(); // force-exit fallback
  });
}

process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => {
  console.error({ msg: 'unhandled_rejection', reason });
});
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error({ msg: 'uncaught_exception', err: err.message, stack: err.stack });
  process.exit(1);
});

module.exports = app;
```

